#Question 3:	Reformat FASTA headers to a standardized naming scheme. You have been given a FASTA file, hw2.fa containing mitochondrial genomes sequences from hundreds of samples. 
#a.	Create a new file containing only the sample names named hw2_fasta_names.txt
#b.	Rewrite each header in the fasta file so that anything beginning with and including the first underscore (_) is removed, leaving only the base ID.
#Sequence lines must remain unchanged. Save these to a file called hw2_modID.fa
#question 3, start by head hw2.fa
head hw2.fa
#got a bunch of nucleotides, but I think each line starts with “>” so in theory we should be able to grep it amf put it into a new file. 
grep ">" hw2.fa > hw2_fasta_names.txt
head hw2_fasta_names.txt
#seems to have worked
awk '/^>/ {sub(/_.*/, "", $0)} 1' hw2.fa > hw2_modID.fa
# using the awk command we can search for the “>” sign and substitute it. Based on how the files are named, all have the _. Then the astrix says plus everything else, put nothing, in column 0 of the h22.fa file and print to modify


#Question 3 solution in class
grep -P '>' hw2.fa > hw2_fasta_names.txt
sed -E 's/^>([^_])+).*/>\1/' hw2.fa > hw2_modID.fa
 

